$ webp --help
Command-line tools for the webpkit WebP codec: libwebp-style cwebp (lossy by default, -lossless for VP8L) / dwebp and the webp brand tool.

Usage: webp [OPTIONS] [INPUTS]...
       webp <COMMAND>

Commands:
  decode       Decode a WebP file to PNG (default), PPM/PAM, or raw pixels
  encode       Encode an image (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM/raw) into a WebP file
  convert      Batch-convert many images (or directories) to WebP, in parallel
  info         Print a summary of a WebP file (size, alpha, metadata, animation)
  diff         Compare two images: report PSNR and the largest per-channel difference
  doctor       Diagnose the environment: PATH drop-in shadows, config, terminal, threads
  config       Show resolved settings and where each came from (args, env, file, default)
  explain      Explain an exit code: what a failing run's status number means
  completions  Print a shell completion script
  man          Print a man page in roff, for `man -l -` or a package's man directory
  help         Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)

Arguments:
  [INPUTS]...
          Images or directories. A WebP is decoded to PNG; anything else is encoded

Options:
  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output file, or a directory for many inputs; default: beside each input

  -q, --quality <QUALITY>
          Lossy quality 0-100 (higher = larger, closer to source); selects lossy

      --lossless
          Force lossless (VP8L) encoding

      --lossy
          Force lossy (VP8) encoding

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort [default: balanced, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - fast:     Fastest: literal + subtract-green only
          - balanced: Balanced (the default): LZ77 + color cache
          - best:     Smallest: adds Tier 3 forward transforms and meta-Huffman on top of Balanced

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to embed: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

      --crop <X,Y,W,H>
          Crop before encoding: `x,y,width,height` in pixels (applied before --resize)

      --resize <WxH>
          Resize before encoding: `WxH` (use 0 on one axis to keep aspect)

  -r, --recursive
          Recurse into subdirectories

      --force
          Overwrite an existing derived output

      --no-clobber
          Skip an existing derived output instead of failing (still exits 0)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

  -V, --version
          Print version

$ webp decode --help
Decode a WebP file to PNG (default), PPM/PAM, or raw pixels

Usage: webp decode [OPTIONS] --output <OUTPUT> [INPUT]

Arguments:
  [INPUT]
          Input `.webp` file; `-` (the default) reads stdin
          
          [default: -]

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output path; `-` writes stdout

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --format <FORMAT>
          Output format; defaults to the `-o` extension, else PNG

          Possible values:
          - png: PNG, RGBA8
          - ppm: Netpbm binary PPM (`P6`, RGB; alpha dropped)
          - pam: Netpbm binary PAM (`P7`, RGBA)
          - raw: Raw row-major pixels in the requested `--layout`

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --layout <LAYOUT>
          Byte order for raw output only

          Possible values:
          - rgba8: `R, G, B, A`
          - argb8: `A, R, G, B`
          - bgra8: `B, G, R, A`
          
          [default: rgba8]

      --frames <FRAMES>
          For animations: which frames to emit

          Possible values:
          - first: Only the first composited frame (the default)
          - all:   Every composited frame, numbered `<stem>-000.<ext>`, ...

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --frame <FRAME>
          For animations: emit only this 0-based frame

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to carry into the output: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp encode --help
Encode an image (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM/raw) into a WebP file

Usage: webp encode [OPTIONS] --output <OUTPUT> [INPUT]

Arguments:
  [INPUT]
          Input image (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM/raw); `-` (default) reads stdin
          
          [default: -]

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output `.webp` file; `-` writes stdout

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --input-format <INPUT_FORMAT>
          Input format; defaults to the extension, else the magic bytes, else raw

          Possible values:
          - png:  PNG (any color type; normalized to RGBA8)
          - ppm:  Netpbm binary PPM (`P6`, RGB)
          - pam:  Netpbm binary PAM (`P7`, RGBA)
          - jpeg: JPEG (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - gif:  GIF (first frame as a still; whole-file animation is a separate path)
          - tiff: TIFF (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - bmp:  BMP (decoded to RGBA8; needs the `formats` feature)
          - raw:  Raw row-major pixels; requires `--width`/`--height`/`--layout`

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --width <WIDTH>
          Raw-input width in pixels (required for raw input)

      --height <HEIGHT>
          Raw-input height in pixels (required for raw input)

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

      --layout <LAYOUT>
          Byte order for raw input only

          Possible values:
          - rgba8: `R, G, B, A`
          - argb8: `A, R, G, B`
          - bgra8: `B, G, R, A`
          
          [default: rgba8]

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort [default: balanced, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - fast:     Fastest: literal + subtract-green only
          - balanced: Balanced (the default): LZ77 + color cache
          - best:     Smallest: adds Tier 3 forward transforms and meta-Huffman on top of Balanced

      --lossless
          Force lossless (VP8L). The default is source-derived: JPEG → lossy, else lossless

      --lossy
          Encode lossily (VP8) instead of losslessly (VP8L)

  -q, --quality <QUALITY>
          Lossy quality 0-100 (higher = larger, closer to source); selects --lossy

      --crop <X,Y,W,H>
          Crop before encoding: `x,y,width,height` in pixels (applied before --resize)

      --resize <WxH>
          Resize before encoding: `WxH` (use 0 on one axis to keep aspect)

      --target-size <SIZE>
          Target output size, e.g. `200k` or `2M`, found by searching lossy quality.
          
          Lossy only: it bisects quality until the encoded file fits. With `-v`, the search is printed. Cannot combine with `--lossless`.

      --min-psnr <DB>
          Target reconstruction PSNR floor in dB (lossy only; pairs with --target-size)

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to embed: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all — kinder than cwebp)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp convert --help
Batch-convert many images (or directories) to WebP, in parallel

Usage: webp convert [OPTIONS] <INPUTS>...

Arguments:
  <INPUTS>...
          Input images and/or directories (PNG/JPEG/GIF/TIFF/BMP/PPM/PAM)

Options:
  -o, --output <OUTPUT>
          Output directory (created outputs are `<stem>.webp`); default: beside input

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

  -m, --method <METHOD>
          Encoder effort (ignored with --optimize) [default: balanced, or from env/config]

          Possible values:
          - fast:     Fastest: literal + subtract-green only
          - balanced: Balanced (the default): LZ77 + color cache
          - best:     Smallest: adds Tier 3 forward transforms and meta-Huffman on top of Balanced

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --lossless
          Force lossless (VP8L). The default is source-derived: JPEG → lossy, else lossless

      --lossy
          Encode lossily (VP8) instead of losslessly (VP8L)

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

  -q, --quality <QUALITY>
          Lossy quality 0-100 (higher = larger, closer to source); selects --lossy

      --optimize
          Try every lossless effort level and keep the smallest output

  -r, --recursive
          Recurse into subdirectories

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Metadata to embed: all,none,icc,exif,xmp (default: all)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp info --help
Print a summary of a WebP file (size, alpha, metadata, animation)

Usage: webp info [OPTIONS] [INPUT]

Arguments:
  [INPUT]
          Input `.webp` file; `-` (the default) reads stdin
          
          [default: -]

Options:
      --json
          Print the report as JSON instead of text.
          
          One object, with a `schema` field to pin. Nothing is decoded either way, so this is cheap on any size of file.

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp diff --help
Compare two images: report PSNR and the largest per-channel difference.

Both inputs are decoded to RGBA (a WebP, or any readable image), so a source and its WebP, or two WebP files, can be compared. With `--min-psnr`, exit 1 when the PSNR is below the threshold — the grep/diff convention, for CI gates.

Usage: webp diff [OPTIONS] <A> <B>

Arguments:
  <A>
          The first image (a WebP, or any readable format)

  <B>
          The second image, compared against the first (same dimensions required)

Options:
      --min-psnr <DB>
          Fail (exit 1) if the RGB PSNR is below this many decibels

  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --json
          Print the comparison as JSON instead of text

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp doctor --help
Diagnose the environment: PATH drop-in shadows, config, terminal, threads.

Exits 0 even with warnings; 1 only on a real error (an invalid config file).

Usage: webp doctor [OPTIONS]

Options:
  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --threads <N>
          Worker threads for parallel work; 0 (the default) uses one per core.
          
          One global thread pool is built, which the encoder's parallel `best` search draws from too — so this single number bounds every layer of parallelism, batch conversion and per-image search alike.

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

$ webp config --help
Show resolved settings and where each came from (args, env, file, default).

Settings resolve highest-priority-first: command-line arguments, then `WEBP_*` environment variables, then a `webp.toml` (found by walking up from the working directory, then in your user config directory), then the built-in defaults. Each value is printed with its origin.

Usage: webp config [OPTIONS] [COMMAND]

Commands:
  get   Print a single setting's resolved value, with nothing else
  help  Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)

Options:
  -v, --verbose...
          Print per-stage detail on stderr

      --json
          Print the resolved settings as JSON (stable key order)

      --quiet
          Suppress all non-error output.
          
          Long-only: `-q` is `--quality`. A bare `webp -q photo.png` therefore reads `photo.png` as a quality value and fails; use `--quiet` to silence output.

      --color <WHEN>
          auto, always, or never
          
          `CLICOLOR_FORCE` and `NO_COLOR` are honored, and an explicit `--color` outranks both. Left alone, messages are colored only when stderr is a terminal — so a pipe or a log file never receives escape codes.
          
          [default: auto]

      --template
          Print a commented `webp.toml` template to stdout

      --quality <0-100>
          Override: lossy quality 0-100

      --effort <EFFORT>
          Override: encoder effort

          Possible values:
          - fast:     Fastest: literal + subtract-green only
          - balanced: Balanced (the default): LZ77 + color cache
          - best:     Smallest: adds Tier 3 forward transforms and meta-Huffman on top of Balanced

      --codec <CODEC>
          Override: lossless or lossy

          Possible values:
          - lossless: Lossless (VP8L)
          - lossy:    Lossy (VP8)

      --metadata <METADATA>
          Override: metadata to carry (all,none,icc,exif,xmp)

          Possible values:
          - all:  Keep ICC, Exif, and XMP
          - none: Strip everything (a bare `VP8L` output)
          - icc:  Keep the ICC color profile
          - exif: Keep Exif
          - xmp:  Keep XMP

      --threads <THREADS>
          Override: worker threads (0 = one per core)

      --max-pixels <N|none>
          Override: decode pixel cap (N, 300M, 2G, or none)

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

